**user**:
> What are some alternatives to a pie chart for providing a visual description of how several (labeled) parts combine to make a whole?
**assistant**:
> There are several alternatives to a pie chart for providing a visual representation of how several parts combine to make a whole. Here are a few:
> 
> 1. **Bar Chart**: A bar chart can be used to compare parts of a whole across categories. The length of the bars represent the size of the category in relation to the others.
> 
> 2. **Stacked Bar Chart**: This is similar to a bar chart, but bars are divided into segments that represent different categories. The length of each segment represents the size of that category.
> 
> 3. **Column Chart**: Similar to a bar chart, but the bars are displayed vertically. This can make it easier to read labels on the horizontal axis.
> 
> 4. **Stacked Column Chart**: Similar to a stacked bar chart, but the bars are displayed vertically.
> 
> 5. **Donut Chart**: A donut chart is similar to a pie chart, but it has a hole in the middle, which can make it easier to compare the size of different categories.
> 
> 6. **Treemap**: A treemap is a rectangular plot divided into segments. The size of each segment represents the size of the category. This can be useful for displaying hierarchies.
> 
> 7. **Waffle Chart**: A waffle chart is a grid of small squares, where each square represents a certain proportion of the whole. Different categories can be represented by different colors.
> 
> 8. **Area Chart**: An area chart can be used to represent the proportion of different categories over time. The area under the line represents the size of the category.
> 
> 9. **Sankey Diagram**: A Sankey diagram shows the flow of data between different parts of a system. The width of the arrows is proportional to the flow quantity.
> 
> 10. **Pictogram Chart (or Pictograph)**: Pictograms use icons to represent data counts or quantities. They can be a simple and intuitive way to show proportions or frequencies, especially for audiences that may not be as comfortable with more abstract charts.
> 
> Each of these options has strengths and weaknesses, and the best one to use will depend on the specific data and audience.
